---
import MainLayout from "../../../layouts/MainLayout.astro";
import MotuSidebar from '../../../components/MotuSidebar.astro';

const title = "Converters & Sample Rates — UltraLite-mk3";
const description = "Converter and sample-rate capabilities.";
---

<MainLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <div class="flex gap-8 items-start">
    <div class="w-[250px] flex-shrink-0">
    <MotuSidebar />
    </div>
    <article class="prose">
      <h1>Converters & Sample Rates</h1>

      <h2>Specifications</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Bit depth:</strong> 24-bit ADC and DAC on all analog inputs and outputs.</li>
        <li><strong>Sample rates:</strong> 44.1, 48, 88.2, 96, 176.4, and 192 kHz. Note: at 176.4/192 kHz, available I/O count is reduced.</li>
        <li><strong>Dynamic range (EIN):</strong> approximately 116 dB — well above the threshold of audibility for any noise floor concern in a home studio environment.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Practical Sample Rate Guide</h2>
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Sample Rate</th><th>Use Case</th><th>File Size Impact</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>44.1 kHz</td><td>Standard music production (CD quality)</td><td>Baseline</td></tr>
          <tr><td>48 kHz</td><td>Video/post-production standard</td><td>+9% vs 44.1</td></tr>
          <tr><td>96 kHz</td><td>High-resolution recording (recommended for Hydrasynth wavetable content)</td><td>2× baseline</td></tr>
          <tr><td>192 kHz</td><td>Mastering and archival; reduced I/O count</td><td>4× baseline</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Why 24-bit Matters for This Gear</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Hydrasynth Explorer:</strong> recording at 24-bit/96 kHz captures the full harmonic resolution of wavetable morphing. The WAVELIST morph positions between waveforms produce subtle transient details that 16-bit would quantise away. At 96 kHz, upper harmonic content above 20 kHz (present in complex waveforms) is preserved during the recording and only filtered at the output stage.</li>
        <li><strong>Yamaha P-225:</strong> the GHC keybed produces genuine dynamic range across piano octaves. 24-bit provides 144 dB theoretical dynamic range — enough headroom to capture both the quietest pianissimo and the loudest fortissimo without compression or gain rides.</li>
        <li><strong>Shure SM58:</strong> dynamic mics produce a lower signal level. Recording at 24-bit means you can use more preamp gain without noise becoming audible — benefiting from the MOTU preamp's ~116 dB dynamic range directly.</li>
      </ul>

      <img src="https://cdn-data.motu.com/site/images/ultralite-mk3/os-support.jpg" alt="OS support" class="w-48" />
    </article>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
